        "date":  "2026-06-26",
        "theme":  "Enterprise",
        "summary":  "A Work AI Institute study reveals that while digital workers save an average of 11 hours weekly through AI adoption, approximately 6.4 hours are consumed by \u0027botsitting\u0027 ΓÇö verifying outputs, debugging errors, and managing hallucinations. Inadequate governance frameworks and insufficient employee training leave organizations unable to realize genuine productivity gains, as unverified AI-generated work creates downstream rework that offsets individual time savings at the organizational level.",
        "execSummary":  "AI adoption at scale is creating a hidden productivity drain: employees spend more than half their AI-generated time savings simply babysitting the AI\u0027s output. This finding reframes the ROI conversation ΓÇö deploying AI without robust governance and training doesn\u0027t save time, it just relocates effort. For customer-support and operations leaders, this signals that agent deployment without quality frameworks and escalation guardrails will disappoint on cost-reduction targets. The 6.4 hours of botsitting per 11 hours saved is the key metric to bring into executive conversations about realistic AI ROI timelines.",
        "vendorLean":  "Neutral",
